<p>Antifouling paint is the single most important protective system on the underwater portion of your hull, yet most boat owners know surprisingly little about how it actually works. They know it's copper-coloured, it's expensive, and it needs redoing every year or two. Beyond that, it remains a mystery — and that lack of understanding leads to poor decisions about when to repaint, which product to choose, and crucially, how to clean a coated hull without causing damage.</p>

<h2>What Antifouling Paint Actually Does</h2>

<p>Antifouling paint works by incorporating biocidal compounds — typically copper-based — that leach slowly from the paint surface into the surrounding water. This creates a thin boundary layer of biocide concentration immediately around your hull that's toxic to fouling organisms. Barnacle larvae, algae spores, and other colonising organisms encounter this layer and either die or are discouraged from settling.</p>

<p>The key word is "slowly." Antifouling isn't a one-time chemical barrier. It's a slow-release system that depletes over time. Every day your boat sits in the water, a tiny amount of biocide leaches away. Eventually, the rate of release drops below the threshold needed to deter fouling, and organisms begin to settle despite the coating. This is why antifouling paint has a finite lifespan and needs periodic renewal.</p>

<h2>Ablative vs Hard Antifouling</h2>

<p>There are two fundamentally different types of antifouling paint, and understanding the distinction matters for cleaning decisions.</p>

<p><strong>Ablative (self-polishing) antifouling</strong> is designed to gradually wear away over time, constantly exposing fresh biocide-laden paint beneath. Think of it like a bar of soap — the surface dissolves slowly, keeping the active ingredient at the surface. Water movement across the hull accelerates this ablation, which is why boats used regularly tend to get more life from ablative antifouling than boats that sit stationary. The downside is that the paint layer gets progressively thinner, and aggressive cleaning can accelerate this thinning beyond what's desirable.</p>

<p><strong>Hard (non-ablative) antifouling</strong> doesn't erode. It forms a durable shell that releases biocide without sacrificing the paint matrix. The advantage is longevity — hard antifouling can last multiple seasons without repainting. The disadvantage is that once the biocide is exhausted, you're left with an inert, rough surface that's actually attractive to fouling organisms. And because the paint doesn't wear away, fouling can build up on top of it, requiring more aggressive cleaning to remove.</p>

<h2>Why Cleaning Method Matters</h2>

<p>Here's where this becomes directly relevant to hull cleaning decisions. The cleaning method you choose interacts with your antifouling type in ways that can either extend or dramatically shorten its useful life.</p>

<p><strong>Pressure washing</strong> (typically done during a lift-out) is the most destructive cleaning method for ablative antifouling. High-pressure water strips the soft paint surface aggressively, removing far more coating material than necessary to clear the fouling. A single pressure wash can remove 50-100 microns of ablative paint — accelerating the depletion of your coating by months.</p>

<p><strong>Metal scrapers and wire brushes</strong> (used by some dive teams) create uneven wear patterns on ablative coatings and can gouge through to the primer or bare substrate. On hard antifouling, scrapers can crack the brittle coating, creating entry points for moisture and reducing adhesion.</p>

<p><strong>Certified nylon brushes</strong> (used by our Keelcrab Pro system) provide sufficient mechanical action to remove fouling — including barnacles and established algae — without significantly eroding ablative paint or damaging hard coatings. The A.N.C.C.P. certification specifically validates that these brushes clean effectively within safe tolerances for standard antifouling systems. This is why we chose brush-based robotic cleaning over pressure-based or scraper-based alternatives.</p>

<h2>How to Extend Your Antifouling's Life</h2>

<p>Based on our experience cleaning hundreds of hulls across South Devon, here are the practical steps that measurably extend antifouling lifespan:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Clean regularly, clean early.</strong> The single most effective thing you can do is clean before fouling hardens and bonds. Removing soft biofilm and juvenile barnacles preserves far more paint than removing established hard fouling. A quarterly or bi-monthly schedule catches fouling in its easy-to-remove stages.</li>
  <li><strong>Use the right cleaning method.</strong> Nylon brush cleaning removes fouling without stripping paint. Avoid pressure washing except when preparing for a full repaint. If your diver uses metal scrapers, ask them to switch to nylon pads.</li>
  <li><strong>Choose the right paint for your usage pattern.</strong> If your boat sits on a mooring for months between uses, hard antifouling may suit better because it doesn't rely on water flow for activation. If you sail regularly, ablative antifouling's self-polishing action works in your favour.</li>
  <li><strong>Don't over-apply.</strong> More coats doesn't necessarily mean better protection. Follow the manufacturer's recommended film thickness. Excessive build-up can cause adhesion problems and inter-coat delamination.</li>
  <li><strong>Monitor with inspections.</strong> A visual hull inspection between seasons shows you exactly how your antifouling is performing, where it's thinning, and whether you need a full repaint or just touch-ups before the next season.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When to Repaint</h2>

<p>The decision to repaint is ideally informed by evidence, not habit. Too many boat owners repaint annually because "that's what you do" — wasting money on a full application when their existing coating still has life in it. Others stretch the interval too long, ending up with inadequate protection and heavy fouling that damages the underlying primer.</p>

<p>A visual inspection in early spring reveals the true condition of your antifouling. If the biocide layer is still thick and even, you probably have another season in it. If you can see primer showing through in high-wear areas (waterline, leading edge of keel, rudder), it's time for touch-ups at minimum. If the coating is universally thin or depleted, a full repaint is the right call.</p>

<p>We provide this information in every inspection report — giving you the data to make an informed decision rather than a habitual one.</p>

